  monumentInformation:
    monumentInformation:
    - title: Who Built It
      details:
      - The Brihadeeswara Temple was commissioned by the Chola emperor Rajaraja I
        as a symbol of his power and devotion to Lord Shiva.
      - It was designed and constructed by skilled artisans and architects under
        the Chola dynasty, with Raja Raja I overseeing the temple's grandeur and
        detail.
    - title: Where It Is Located
      details:
      - The Brihadeeswara Temple is located in Thanjavur, Tamil Nadu, India, which
        was the capital of the Chola Empire at the time of its construction.
      - The temple stands within the heart of the city, surrounded by lush grounds,
        and is part of a UNESCO World Heritage Site known as the 'Great Living Chola
        Temples.'
    - title: When It Was Built
      details:
      - The construction of the Brihadeeswara Temple began around 1003 AD and was
        completed in 1010 AD, making it over a thousand years old.
      - The temple was completed during the height of the Chola Empire, reflecting
        their architectural mastery and artistic achievements.
    - title: How Is It Protected By
      details:
      - The Brihadeeswara Temple is protected as a UNESCO World Heritage Site, recognising
        its cultural and historical importance globally.
      - The temple is also maintained by the Archaeological Survey of India (ASI),
        ensuring its preservation and conservation as a living monument.
    - title: Why It Was Built
      details:
      - Rajaraja I built the Brihadeeswara Temple as a dedication to Lord Shiva,
        specifically to honour him as 'Rajarajeshwara,' meaning the 'Lord of Rajaraja.'
      - The temple was also constructed to symbolise the might and wealth of the
        Chola Empire, showcasing their dominance in architecture, culture, and devotion.
